In article d5r@ugle.unit.no, rolfm@pluto.er.sintef.no (Rolf Michelsen) writes:
> In article <2ju13q$h4i@geraldo.cc.utexas.edu>, coyne@thing1.cc.utexas.edu () writes:
> |> I have read a tale of the British tapping into a phone line outside
> |> the French embassy in London and recovering the clear text from the
> |> encrypted communication to Paris during the Suez Canal crisis.  That
> |> was quite a while ago.  The French fed clear text from a teletype
> |> paper tape to a cypher machine to another teletype that generated the
> |> encrypted signal.  They were unable to affect the outcome of the crisis.
> |> 
> |> Another time they were out with a radio direction finding van and were
> |> able to hear the received signal on the local oscilator of the
> |> receiver.  They did not figure out that the bad guy must have been the
> |> other car in the parking lot where they were waiting until he had
> |> left.
> |> 
> |> I believe these tales and other equally interesting ones were in a book
> |> called "Spycatcher."
> 
> Yes, you find these tales in "Spycatcher" and the more recent "Spycatcher's Encyclopedia of Espionage".  Both written by Peter Wright who was once at MI5.
